R data manipulation and joining

Height and Weight

In this exercise, we are going to explore a dataset of height and weight of teens

To load this data:

tbl <- read.csv(file='heightweight.csv')
tbl

To explore this data, you can use the dplyr package (which has a variety of useful methods to filter, aggregate, and sort data frames), built-in R functions, or any other package you are familiar with.

Explore the data using the tools you have. You can use the summary function, plot some of the data or look at histograms, and so on. Try the following questions:

  1. Calculate the weight in Kg
tbl <- mutate(tbl,weightKg=weightLb/2.2)
tbl
  1. Calculate the height in meters
tbl <- mutate(tbl,heightm=heightIn*0.0254)
tbl
  1. Calculate BMI as kg/m2
tbl <- mutate(tbl,bmi=weightKg/(heightm*heightm))
tbl
  1. Plot the BMI by gender using a box plot
boxplot(tbl$bmi ~ tbl$sex)

  1. What is the min, max, mean and median height per gender?
summarize(group_by(tbl,sex),mean.height=mean(heightIn),min.height=min(heightIn),max.height=max(heightIn),median.height=median(heightIn))

Bacterial Community

In this exercise, we are going to explore the bacterial communities of 4 synthetic samples. This dataset contains the counts of reads that are classified into each taxa per sample. The first column is the taxonomic level where:

  1. Kingdom
  2. Phylum
  3. Class
  4. Order
  5. Family
  6. Genus
  7. Species

To load the data use the command:

mock <-read.table(file="mock_community.txt",sep='\t',header=TRUE)

To explore this data, you can use the dplyr package (which has a variety of useful methods to filter, aggregate, and sort data frames), built-in R functions, or any other package you are familiar with.

Explore the data using the tools you have. You can use the summary function, plot some of the data or look at histograms, and so on. Try the following questions:

  1. What is the most abundant genus for each community?
abun <- filter(mock, taxlevel == 6)
mock1 <- abun[order(abun$Mock1, decreasing = T),][1,]
mock2 <- abun[order(abun$Mock2, decreasing = T),][1,]
mock3 <- abun[order(abun$Mock3, decreasing = T),][1,]
mock4 <- abun[order(abun$Mock4, decreasing = T),][1,]
arrange(abun, desc(Mock1))
arrange(abun, desc(Mock2))
arrange(abun, desc(Mock3))
arrange(abun, desc(Mock4))
  1. Which phylum has the highest read counts for all 4 samples?
rcounts <- filter(mock, taxlevel == 2)
rcounts <- mutate(rcounts, TotalAbund = rowSums(rcounts[,3:6]))
#rcounts <- rcounts[order(rcounts$TotalAbund, decreasing = TRUE),][1,c(2,7)]
rcounts <- arrange(rcounts, desc(TotalAbund))[1,c(2,7)]
rcounts
  1. Calculate the averge number of reads for each phyla
mean.reads <- filter(mock, taxlevel ==2)
mean.reads <- mutate(mean.reads, phylaMeans = rowMeans(mean.reads[,3:6]))
mean.reads

4.Create a new table with the sample name and the ratio of bacteroidetes/firmicutes.

bactero <- t(filter(mock, taxon == 'Bacteroidetes'))[3:6,,drop=FALSE]

ratios <- mutate(ratios, ratio = Bacteroidetes/Firmicutes)
rownames(ratios) <- paste0("mock",seq(1,4,1))
ratios
  1. Which sample has the highest ratio?
mock1
  1. Create a table with just the genera (genus ie taxlevel=6). Add the total number of reads per genera and sort the table by the total.
rcounts <- filter(mock, taxlevel == 6)
rcounts <- mutate(rcounts, TotalAbund = rowSums(rcounts[,3:6]))
#rcounts <- rcounts[order(rcounts$TotalAbund, decreasing = TRUE),]
rcounts <- arrange(rcounts, desc(TotalAbund))
rcounts
  1. Create a heatmap or stack bar plot of the genera by sample.
library(pheatmap)
zscores <- scale(rcounts[,3:6])
rownames(zscores) <- rcounts$taxon
pheatmap(zscores, fontsize_row = 5)

  1. Now load a second table of real samples:
real <-read.table(file="real_community.txt",sep='\t',header=TRUE)
  1. Join mock with real
join.tbl <- inner_join(mock, real)
Joining, by = c("taxlevel", "taxon")
join.tbl
  1. Create a table at any taxa level (ie phylum, order, etc) and plot taxonomic abundance at of samples with stack barplots
library(reshape)
library(ggplot2)
total <- as.data.frame(colSums(join.tbl[,3:8]))
colnames(total)<-"nseqs"
total$sample <- rownames(total)
taxct <- melt(join.tbl,id.vars=c('taxon','taxlevel'))
names(taxct) <- c('taxname','level','sample','taxct')
taxct <- merge(taxct,total,by='sample')
taxct <- mutate(taxct,perc=round(taxct/nseqs, digits = 7))
min.seq<- min(total$nseqs)
taxct <- mutate(taxct,norm=min.seq*perc)
ggplot(taxct, aes(x = sample, y = perc,fill=taxname)) + geom_bar(stat='identity') + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1), legend.position = 'none')
